{
  "$comment": "Hand-authored cross-language parity corpus for email validation — the SOURCE OF TRUTH for expected behavior. Both runtimes (.NET DcsvIo.D2.Validation.DefaultEmailValidator and TS @dcsv-io/d2-validation DefaultEmailValidator) READ this file and ASSERT each row; neither runtime emits it. All addresses are synthetic — no real PII. Rows exercise happy-path plus adversarial input (null / empty / whitespace / oversized / malformed / unicode / format-edge). 'valid' rows carry the expected 'normalized' (trim + lowercase) form; '!valid' rows carry 'errorKey'. Inputs are either a literal 'input' string or synthesized from 'inputKind' (null | whitespace | oversized) with optional 'char' + 'inputRepeat' (oversized => char.repeat(inputRepeat)) and optional 'suffix' (appended after the repeated block, e.g. oversized char='a' inputRepeat=250 suffix='@b.co' => 250 'a's + '@b.co' = a structurally-well-formed 255-char address that exceeds the 254 limit). Both runtimes synthesize identically. NOTE on local-part dots: the shared EMAIL_PATTERN is a practical structural check (RFC 5321/5322 practical limits) whose local-part class permits dots in any position, so leading / trailing / consecutive dots in the LOCAL part (e.g. '.a@b.com', 'a.@b.com', 'a..b@c.com') are accepted on BOTH runtimes — these rows assert that agreed permissive behavior rather than rejection. Domain-side structure is stricter (a trailing dot or missing TLD on the DOMAIN is rejected).",
